Section Summary: In 1820, the remains of a great ancient Egyptian city were discovered in Middle Egypt, and in 1888, a number of clay tablets were found near the ruins of Tell el Amarna. The tablets, written in Babylonian cuneiform, were part of the Egyptian state archives during the reigns of Kings Amenophis III and IV, and consisted mainly of letters from Egyptian officials and foreign kings. The discovery revealed that Babylonian was the language of diplomacy in the East around 1400 B.C. The tablets provided valuable insights into the administration and court of the Egyptian pharaohs, including their relationships with other kingdoms and their internal affairs. The reigns of Amenophis III and IV marked a significant shift in Egyptian culture, with a focus on art, architecture, and religious reform, rather than military conquest.
